Various empirical strategies have been devised to identify the 'causal impact' of education on 
earnings and the approaches used are much better developed than in many other areas of empirical work in 
the social sciences. 2 Existing evidence shows that there is indeed a sizable wage return to education. This is 
true in studies set in different time periods, in different countries and for different demographic groups. Of 
course, the estimated returns do differ with observable characteristics (e.g. returns to university degrees 
vary according to university attended and subject studied), but there is clear evidence of a significant 2. 
